Wraps `cargo-machete` to report unused dependencies as structured FAIL lines, exiting nonzero if any are found or if the tool errors. Unlike `cargo deny`, machete works offline — it parses Cargo.toml and greps sources only, requiring no network or full dependency graph resolution — so it fits the static-check context alongside cycle_check.sh.

Missing cargo-machete is a loud error (exit 1), not a skip, because "no unused deps" is enforced directly here; silently mapping the missing binary to skipped would make ctx-verify's pass misleading.

The script captures machete's output (which lists unused deps per crate), parses each line via awk to extract the crate path and dependency name, and emits one `FAIL: <path> unused dependency '<name>'` per violation to stderr. If machete exits nonzero but produces no parseable unused-dependency output (e.g., a manifest read error), it surfaces `FAIL: cargo machete failed` to keep the failure visible. Exit code is 0 only if no violations and no errors.